types.name: InstanceSearchQuery
types.description:
A query for searching instances.
There are three main components to a search query:
1. Filters: what is the set of instances we're searching over?
2. Scoring: how do we determine which instances are most relevant?
3. Ordering: how do we represent or layout the set of instances?
A slightly different intuition pump:
You start with the entire dataset. Filters remove things we definitely dont
want, leaving us with documents that we might want. Scoring helps us figure out
how to go from things we might want into things we do want. Order tells us how
to serve the results.
A third intuition pump:
1. Filters are O(1) -- you can decide whether to keep a document or not from
   the document and the input alone.
2. Scores are O(n) -- you can only decide if a document is useful after you've
   seen/calculated scores on all the documents.
3. Ordering is O(nlog(n)) -- it's just a sort.
There's a ton of collision in these concepts because any given field on a data
structure can act as all three. As an example, dateCreated.
- filter: give me only things after 2020
- scoring: give me documents that are close to 2020
- order: sort by the date
Worse, we often want and expect that collision. The default ordering is always
sort by score, and we often want results with low scores to be removed entirely
as if it was a filter.
The design of our search query interface tries to take the above into account.
We separate the three concepts into three different fields, and mark each as
optional. Depending on what combination of fields is set, we can infer what the
user wants and return the correct results.
If none of the fields are set, we return the maximum number of results allowed
by search, selected and ordered with no defined criteria.

inputFields.name: filter
inputFields.description:
Allows the client to filter out certain results.
All filters are treated as hard filters, meaning that results which don't
match this filter will never be returned.
Filters are computational optimizations. If no filters are set, we may
end up scoring the entire dataset, which can be very expensive.

inputFields.name: first
inputFields.description:
Indicates how many instances should be fetched. These will be the first N
instances matching the rest of this filter.
If unset, will return the maximum number of results allowed by search.

inputFields.name: order
inputFields.description:
Defines the ordering of the results.
If unset, defaults to ordering by descending score, followed by descending
dateCreated.

inputFields.name: score
inputFields.description:
Allows the client to specify how the results should be scored. Scoring is a
relative measure of how well a result matches the query. Higher scores are
better matches.
Strictly speaking, we can do a wide range of useful searches by combining
boolean filters and order alone. Scoring becomes useful when we have to
calculate a relative measure of how well a result fits a query, and then use
that relative measure to define some sort of cut-off or ordering.
For simplicity, we only allow one scoring method to be set at a time. If
unset, we default to a score of 1 for all results.

fields.name: originalResolution
fields.description:
KTX2 textures are remarkably useful in Texture Arrays, a structure where KTX2
textures are concatenated together and treated as one large stitched texture.
However, a requirement of texture arrays is that all stitched together
textures are the same size. This means we often resize most textures into a
fixed size (such as 1024x1024) and the client is responsible for writing a
shader which will consume the stretched texture and resize it to the intended
aspect ratio. We represent this data as the `originalResolution`, the size
that this texture should be when restored to its original aspect ratio and
size.

types.name: Duration
types.description:
A string representing a duration conforming to the ISO8601 standard,
such as: P1W1DT13H23M34S
P is the duration designator (for period) placed at the start of the duration representation.
Y is the year designator that follows the value for the number of years.
M is the month designator that follows the value for the number of months.
W is the week designator that follows the value for the number of weeks.
D is the day designator that follows the value for the number of days.
T is the time designator that precedes the time components of the representation.
H is the hour designator that follows the value for the number of hours.
M is the minute designator that follows the value for the number of minutes.
S is the second designator that follows the value for the number of seconds.

Note the time designator, T, that precedes the time value.

Matches moment.js, Luxon and DateFns implementations
,/. is valid for decimal places and +/- is a valid prefix

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByUrl`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: UNION

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST

types.name: __Directive

A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.
